label: Content-Encoding
info: indicates what content codings have been applied to the representation, beyond those inherent in the media type, and thus what decoding mechanisms have to be applied in order to obtain data in the media type referenced by the Content-Type header field.

label: Content-Language
info: describes the natural language(s) of the intended audience for the representation.

label: Content-Location
info: references a URI that can be used as an identifier for a specific resource corresponding to the representation in this message's payload.

label: Content-Type
info: indicates the media type of the associated representation: either the representation enclosed in the message payload or the selected representation, as determined by the message semantics.

label: Content-Length
info: can provide the anticipated size, as a decimal number of octets, for a potential payload body.

label: Content-Range
info: is sent in a single part 206 (Partial Content) response to indicate the partial range of the selected representation enclosed as the message payload, sent in each part of a multipart 206 response to indicate the range enclosed within each body part, and sent in 416 (Range Not Satisfiable) responses to provide information about the selected representation.

label: Transfer-Encoding
info: lists the transfer coding names corresponding to the sequence of transfer codings that have been (or will be) applied to the payload body in order to form the message body.

label: Cache-Control
info: is used to specify directives for caches along the request/response chain.

label: Expect
info: is used to indicate that particular server behaviors are required by the client.

label: Host
info: provides the host and port information from the target URI, enabling the origin server to distinguish among resources while servicing requests for multiple host names on a single IP address.

label: HTTP2-Settings
info: A request that upgrades from HTTP/1.1 to HTTP/2 MUST include exactly one HTTP2-Settings header field. The HTTP2-Settings header field is a connection-specific header field that includes parameters that govern the HTTP/2 connection, provided in anticipation of the server accepting the request to upgrade.

label: Max-Forwards
info: provides a mechanism with the TRACE and OPTIONS methods to limit the number of times that the request is forwarded by proxies.

label: Pragma
info: allows backwards compatibility with HTTP/1.0 caches, so that clients can specify a no-cache request that they will understand (as Cache-Control was not defined until HTTP/1.1).

label: Range
info: modifies the method semantics to request transfer of only one or more subranges of the selected representation data, rather than the entire selected representation data.

label: TE
info: indicates what transfer codings, besides chunked, the client is willing to accept in response, and whether or not the client is willing to accept trailer fields in a chunked transfer coding.

label: If-Match
info: can be used to make a request method conditional on the current existence or value of an entity-tag for one or more representations of the target resource.

label: If-Modified-Since
info: can be used with GET or HEAD to make the method conditional by modification date: if the selected representation has not been modified since the time specified in this field, then do not perform the request method; instead, respond as detailed below.

label: If-None-Match
info: can be used to make a request method conditional on not matching any of the current entity-tag values for representations of the target resource.

label: If-Range
info: Informally, its meaning is: if the representation is unchanged, send me the part(s) that I am requesting in Range; otherwise, send me the entire representation.

label: If-Unmodified-Since
info: can be used to make a request method conditional by modification date: if the selected representation has been modified since the time specified in this field, then the server MUST NOT perform the requested operation and MUST instead respond with the 412 (Precondition Failed) status code.

label: Accept
info: can be used to specify certain media types which are acceptable for the response.

label: Accept-Charset
info: can be sent by a user agent to indicate what charsets are acceptable in textual response content.

label: Accept-Encoding
info: can be used by user agents to indicate what response content-codings are acceptable in the response.

label: Accept-Language
info: can be used by user agents to indicate the set of natural languages that are preferred in the response.

label: Authorization
info: allows a user agent to authenticate itself with a server -- usually, but not necessarily, after receiving a 401 (Unauthorized) response.

label: Proxy-Authorization
info: allows the client to identify itself (or its user) to a proxy that requires authentication.

label: DNT
info: defined as the means for expressing a user's tracking preference via HTTP.

label: From
info: contains an Internet email address for a human user who controls the requesting user agent.

label: Referer
info: allows the user agent to specify a URI reference for the resource from which the target URI was obtained (i.e., the referrer, though the field name is misspelled).

label: User-Agent
info: contains information about the user agent originating the request, which is often used by servers to help identify the scope of reported interoperability problems, to work around or tailor responses to avoid particular user agent limitations, and for analytics regarding browser or operating system use.

label: Age
info: conveys the sender's estimate of the amount of time since the response was generated or successfully validated at the origin server.

label: Expires
info: gives the date/time after which the response is considered stale.

label: Date
info: represents the date and time at which the message was originated

label: Location
info: is used in some responses to refer to a specific resource in relation to the response.

label: Retry-After
info: indicates how long the user agent ought to wait before making a follow-up request.

label: Tk
info: defined as an OPTIONAL means for indicating the tracking status that applied to the corresponding request and as a REQUIRED means for indicating that a state-changing request has resulted in an interactive change to the tracking status.

label: Vary
info: describes what parts of a request message, aside from the method and request target, might influence the origin server's process for selecting and representing the response.

label: Warning
info: is used to carry additional information about the status or transformation of a message that might not be reflected in the message.

label: ETag
info: provides the current entity-tag for the selected representation, as determined at the conclusion of handling the request.

label: Last-Modified
info: provides a timestamp indicating the date and time at which the origin server believes the selected representation was last modified, as determined at the conclusion of handling the request.

label: WWW-Authenticate
info: consists of at least one challenge that indicates the authentication scheme(s) and parameters applicable to the effective request URI.

label: Proxy-Authenticate
info: consists of at least one challenge that indicates the authentication scheme(s) and parameters applicable to the proxy for this effective request URI.

label: Accept-Ranges
info: allows a server to indicate that it supports range requests for the target resource.

label: Allow
info: lists the set of methods advertised as supported by the target resource.

label: Server
info: contains information about the software used by the origin server to handle the request, which is often used by clients to help identify the scope of reported interoperability problems, to work around or tailor requests to avoid particular server limitations, and for analytics regarding server or operating system use.

label: Accept-Patch
info: used to specify the patch document formats accepted by the server.

label: Accept-Post
info: indicates server support for specific media types for entity bodies in HTTP POST requests.

label: Access-Control-Allow-Credentials
info: indicates whether the response to request can be exposed when the omit credentials flag is unset

label: Access-Control-Allow-Headers
info: indicates, as part of the response to a preflight request, which header field names can be used during the actual request

label: Access-Control-Allow-Methods
info: indicates, as part of the response to a preflight request, which methods can be used during the actual request

label: Access-Control-Allow-Origin
info: indicates whether a resource can be shared

label: Access-Control-Expose-Headers
info: indicates which headers are safe to expose to the API of a CORS API specification

label: Access-Control-Max-Age
info: indicates how long the results of a preflight request can be cached in a preflight result cache

label: Access-Control-Request-Headers
info: indicates which headers will be used in the actual request as part of the preflight request

label: Access-Control-Request-Method
info: indicates which method will be used in the actual request as part of the preflight request

label: Content-Disposition
info: standard

label: Content-Security-Policy
info: is the preferred mechanism for delivering a CSP policy

label: Content-Security-Policy-Report-Only
info: lets servers experiment with policies by monitoring (rather than enforcing) a policy

label: Cookie
info: standard

label: Forwarded
info: standard

label: Link
info: provides a means for serialising one or more links in HTTP headers.

label: Origin
info: standard

label: Prefer
info: is used to indicate that particular server behaviors are preferred by the client, but not required for successful completion of the request.

label: Preference-Applied
info: MAY be included within a response message as an indication as to which Prefer tokens were honored by the server and applied to the processing of a request.

label: Set-Cookie
info: standard

label: Strict-Transport-Security
info: standard

label: Accept-CH
info: advertise support for Client Hints

label: Accept-Features
info: can be used by a user agent to give information about the presence or absence of certain features in the feature set of the current request.

label: ALPN
info: indicates the application-layer protocol that a client intends to use within the tunnel, or a set of protocols that might be used within the tunnel.

label: Alt-Svc
info: is advertising the availability of alternate services to HTTP/1.1 and HTTP/2.0 clients by adding an Alt-Svc header field to responses.

label: Alternates
info: is used to convey the list of variants bound to a negotiable resource.

label: CH
info: describes an example list of client preferences that the server can use to adapt and optimize the resource to satisfy a given request.

label: Content-Base
info: obsoleted

label: Content-DPR
info: is a number that indicates the ratio between physical pixels over CSS px of the selected image response.

label: Cookie2
info: obsoleted

label: DASL
info: standard

label: DAV
info: standard

label: Depth
info: standard

label: Destination
info: standard

label: DPR
info: is a number that, in requests, indicates the client’s current Device Pixel Ratio (DPR), which is the ratio of physical pixels over CSS px of the layout viewport on the device.

label: Encryption
info: describes the encrypted content encoding(s) that have been applied to a payload body, and therefore how those content encoding(s) can be removed.

label: Encryption-Key
info: can be used to describe the input keying material used in the Encryption header field.

label: If
info: standard

label: If-Schedule-Tag-Match
info: standard

label: Key
info: allows an origin server to describe the cache key for a negotiated response: a short algorithm that can be used upon later requests to determine if the same response is reusable.

label: Last-Event-ID
info: The value of the event source's last event ID string, encoded as UTF-8.

label: Link-Template
info: provides a means for serialising one or more links into HTTP headers.

label: Lock-Token
info: standard

label: MD
info: is a number that, in requests, indicates the client’s maximum downlink speed in megabits per second (Mbps), which is the standardized, or generally accepted, maximum download data rate for the underlying connection technology in use by the client.

label: Negotiate
info: can contain directives for any content negotiation process initiated by the request.

label: Nice
info: indicates that a request is less important than a request that doesn't bear this header.

label: Overwrite
info: standard

label: POE
info: The POE HTTP header is a request-header field whose field-value indicates the version of POE that a client supports.

label: POE-Links
info: The POE-Links HTTP header is an entity-header field whose field-value is a comma-separated list of quoted URI-references (without fragment identifiers) that the origin server asserts to be POE resources. The contents of the POE-Links response header SHOULD correspond to links found in the content of the response body.

label: RW
info: is a number that, in requests, indicates the Resource Width (RW) in CSS px, which is either the display width of the requested resource (e.g. display width of an image), or the layout viewport width if the resource does not have a display width (e.g. a non-image asset).

label: Schedule-Reply
info: standard

label: Schedule-Tag
info: standard

label: Sec-WebSocket-Accept
info: standard

label: Sec-WebSocket-Extensions
info: standard

label: Sec-WebSocket-Key
info: standard

label: Sec-WebSocket-Protocol
info: standard

label: Sec-WebSocket-Version
info: standard

label: Set-Cookie2
info: obsoleted

label: SLUG
info: standard

label: Sunset
info: allows a server to communicate the fact that a resource is expected to become unresponsive at a specific point in time.

label: TCN
info: is used by a server to signal that the resource is transparently negotiated.

label: Timeout
info: standard

label: Variant-Vary
info: can be used in a choice response to record any vary information which applies to the variant data (the entity body combined with some of the entity headers) contained in the response, rather than to the response as a whole.

label: X-Frame-Options
info: indicates a policy that specifies whether the browser should render the transmitted resource within a <frame> or an <iframe>. Servers can declare this policy in the header of their HTTP responses to prevent clickjacking attacks, which ensures that their content is not embedded into other pages or frames.
